h3. Problem Definition

Unlike JIRA, in Crowd I am unable to change the log file name by adjusting CrowHomeLogAppender log4 properties.
 In JIRA, an administrator is able to modify its log file properties, including the log file name, by making changes on JIRAHomeAppender.
 In Crowd, however, an admin needs to comment Crowd's appender and use Apache's generic RollingFileAppender in order to make those changes.
h3. Suggested Solution

To use CrowHomeLogAppender class in order to change log file name (and other properties), as JIRA does.
h3. Workaround

If a Crowd admin wishes to change log file properties in Crowd, they need to:
 # comment this line in {{<crowd_install_dir>/crowd_webapp/WEB-INF/classes/log4j.properties}}:
{code:java}
log4j.appender.crowdlog=com.atlassian.crowd.console.logging.CrowdHomeLogAppender{code}

 # add this line (RollingFileAppender appender class) (see CWD-5454 for more details):
{code:java}
log4j.appender.crowdlog=org.apache.log4j.RollingFileAppender{code}

 # add the following property to the new log appender:
{code:java}
log4j.appender.crowdlog.File=<new_file_name.log>{code}

 # For reference: [Logging And Profiling|https://confluence.atlassian.com/crowd/logging-and-profiling-24248601.html]
 # Restart Crowd, so the changes can be applied

When it's necessary to increase or decrease logging level, that may present a small headache to enable/disable logging, since the logged classes are not displayed in their full classname.

For example, instead of outputing:
{code:java}
com.atlassian.plugin.osgi.factory.OsgiPlugin
{code}
it just outputs:
{code:java}
plugin.osgi.factory.OsgiPlugin
{code}
This is due to the following setup in the log4j.properties:
{code:java}
...
log4j.appender.console.layout.ConversionPattern=%d %t %p [%c{4}] %m%n
...
log4j.appender.crowdlog.layout.ConversionPattern=%d %t %p [%c{4}] %m%n
{code}
 

*Workaround*

Erasing the _"\{4\}"_ after the _\%c_ allows the whole class names to be displayed:
{code:java}
...
log4j.appender.console.layout.ConversionPattern=%d %t %p [%c] %m%n
...
log4j.appender.crowdlog.layout.ConversionPattern=%d %t %p [%c] %m%n{code}

h3. Issue Summary
Synchronization sometimes failed, in the logs we can see the error failed at the *findActiveInne* method. The following errors appear in the logs if there are more than one records returns in *cwd_synchronisation_status* table in the database.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
N/A

h3. Expected Results
synchronization successful without any problem

h3. Actual Results
The below exception is thrown in the atlassian-crowd.log file:
{noformat}
org.hibernate.NonUniqueResultException: query did not return a unique result: 2
at org.hibernate.query.internal.AbstractProducedQuery.uniqueElement(AbstractProducedQuery.java:1487)
at org.hibernate.query.internal.AbstractProducedQuery.uniqueResult(AbstractProducedQuery.java:1457)
at com.atlassian.crowd.dao.directory.DirectorySynchronisationStatusDAOHibernate.findActiveInner(DirectorySynchronisationStatusDAOHibernate.java:29)
at com.atlassian.crowd.dao.directory.DirectorySynchronisationStatusDAOHibernate.findActiveForDirectory(DirectorySynchronisationStatusDAOHibernate.java:23)
{noformat}

h3. Workaround
The following steps should do the trick as it will remove the unfinished syncs from the DB:

# Shutdown Crowd.
# Run the following query against the database where Crowd runs:
{code}
SELECT * FROM cwd_synchronisation_status;
{code}
# Confirm that rows are shown (all with statuses different than "SUCCESS_FULL")
# When confident, run the following query:
{code}
DELETE FROM cwd_synchronisation_status WHERE id IN (<run on each directory ID that is giving us issues>);
{code}
# Run the following to confirm we now have only one row per directory:
{code}
SELECT * FROM cwd_synchronisation_status;
{code}
# Start Crowd and check if the issue is resolved.

According to https://aws.amazon.com/amazon-linux-ami/faqs/#General_Answers:
{quote}
AWS will provide security updates for the last version of Amazon Linux AMI, 2018.03 until June 30, 2020 to facilitate migration to Amazon Linux 2. Amazon Linux 2 offers long-term support until June 30, 2023.
{quote}

This improvement request is to adapt the Quickstart template for Crowd Data Center (https://bitbucket.org/atlassian/atlassian-aws-deployment/src/master/quickstarts/quickstart-crowd-master.template.yaml) to use the newer AMI, "Amazon Linux 2 AMI" as the base image.

h3. Description

Inside +./atlassian-crowd-3.4.0/apache-tomcat/webapps/ROOT/index.html+ you have following lines of code:
{code:java}
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="crowd/console/setup/aui/aui/css/aui.css">
    <script src="crowd/console/setup/aui/aui/js/aui-all.js"></script>{code}
Above paths don't exist:
{code:java}
crowd@host:/opt/c/atlassian-crowd-3.4.0\# ls \-lha crowd-webapp/console/setup/aui/aui/css/aui.css
ls: cannot access 'crowd-webapp/console/setup/aui/aui/css/aui.css': No such file or directory{code}
You shortcuted paths (there is no *aui/aui*, but only one level *aui* now), but didn't change links in *index.html*:
{code:java}
crowd@host:/opt/c/atlassian-crowd-3.4.0\# ls \-lha crowd-webapp/console/setup/aui/css/aui.css
\-rw-r\-\-r\-\- 1 crowd crowd 213K Aug 23  2018 crowd-webapp/console/setup/aui/css/aui.css{code}
The result is a lack of styling on the splash page.

The problem started in *Crowd 3.4.0*. In *3.3.4* everything is fine.
h3. Workaround

Navigate to
{code:java}
 {crowd installation dir}/atlassian-crowd-3.4.0/apache-tomcat/webapps/ROOT{code}
edit {{index.html}} file and change following lines:

from
{code:java}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="crowd/console/setup/aui/aui/css/aui.css">
<script src="crowd/console/setup/aui/aui/js/aui-all.js"></script> {code}
to
{code:java}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="crowd/console/setup/aui/css/aui.css">
    <script src="crowd/console/setup/aui/js/jquery.js"></script>
    <script src="crowd/console/setup/aui/js/aui.js"></script> {code}
